The Ramp MCP server is a tool that enables AI assistants to interact with Ramp's Developer API to analyze financial data [1][2]. It uses an internal ETL pipeline and an ephemeral in-memory SQLite database to manage large datasets and bypass token limitations [1][3]. By exposing tools like load_transactions and execute_query, it allows LLMs to run SQL queries against your business data for reporting and analysis [2][4][3].

To set it up, create a client via the Ramp developer portal, grant the necessary scopes, and configure your MCP client with your credentials [1][5]. For Claude Desktop, add the server to your claude_desktop_config.json:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "ramp-mcp": {
      "command": "uv",
      "args": [
        "--directory",
        "/<ABSOLUTE-PATH-TO>/ramp-mcp",
        "run",
        "ramp-mcp",
        "-s",
        "transactions:read,reimbursements:read"
      ],
      "env": {
        "RAMP_CLIENT_ID": "<CLIENT_ID>",
        "RAMP_CLIENT_SECRET": "<CLIENT_SECRET>",
        "RAMP_ENV": "<demo|prd>"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Separately, Ramp also offers a "Developer MCP" server, which is an unauthenticated, read-only server used solely for accessing Ramp’s public API documentation and OpenAPI schemas [6].
